<title>The volume of an irregular tetrahedron</title>
<!-- InstanceEndEditable --> <!-- InstanceBeginEditable name=3D"head" --><!=
-- InstanceEndEditable -->
</head>
<body bgcolor=3D"#ffffff">

<table width=3D"100%">
  <tbody><tr>=20
    <td width=3D"13%" rowspan=3D"2">&nbsp;</td>
    <td width=3D"14%"><p><img src=3D"https://mathcentral.uregina.ca/qq/data=
base/qq.09.03/MCIcon.gif" width=3D"80" height=3D"72"></p></td>
    <td width=3D"62%"><div align=3D"center"><font color=3D"#000066" size=3D=
"+3">Quandaries=20
        and Queries</font><font size=3D"+3"></font></div></td>
    <td width=3D"11%" rowspan=3D"2">&nbsp;</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>=20
    <td colspan=3D"2"><p>&nbsp;</p>
      <!-- InstanceBeginEditable name=3D"question" -->
      <p><font size=3D"+1">Secondary<br>
        Student</font></p>
      <p><font size=3D"+1">How do I calculate the volume of an irregular sh=
aped tetrahedron
          where:-<br>
        side a =3D 1.4 m<br>
        side b =3D 1.4 m<br>
        side c =3D 1.2 m<br>
        and height =3D 0.75 m at the junction of sides a and b.</font></p>
      <p><font size=3D"+1">Thank you in anticipation</font></p>
      <p><font size=3D"+1">Peter </font></p>
      <!-- InstanceEndEditable --></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>=20
    <td width=3D"13%">&nbsp;</td>
    <td colspan=3D"2"><p>&nbsp;</p>
      <!-- InstanceBeginEditable name=3D"answer" -->
      <p><font size=3D"+1">Hi Peter,</font></p>
      <p><font size=3D"+1">The volume follows from a  result
        that says if you take some region R in the plane with an area, some=
 point
        P not
        in the plane and form a cone by joining every point on the boundary=
 of
      R to P with a straight line then the volume of the cone is&nbsp;</fon=
t></p>
      <blockquote>
        <p><font size=3D"+1"><sup>1</sup>/<sub>3</sub>&nbsp;<img src=3D"htt=
ps://mathcentral.uregina.ca/qq/database/qq.09.03/multiply.gif" width=3D"10"=
 height=3D"9">&nbsp;(the
          area of the base)&nbsp;<img src=3D"https://mathcentral.uregina.ca=
/qq/database/qq.09.03/multiply.gif" width=3D"10" height=3D"9">&nbsp;(the
          height).</font></p>
      </blockquote>
      <p align=3D"center"><font size=3D"+1"><img src=3D"https://mathcentral=
.uregina.ca/qq/database/qq.09.03/peter2.1.gif" width=3D"149" height=3D"160"=
></font></p>
      <p align=3D"left"><font size=3D"+1">By your description you have a te=
trahedron with a base
        triangle having sides of lengths a, b and c and a vertex P which is=
 0.75
        m above the plane
        containing the base triangle. </font></p>
      <p align=3D"center"><font size=3D"+1"><img src=3D"https://mathcentral=
.uregina.ca/qq/database/qq.09.03/peter2.2.gif" width=3D"213" height=3D"197"=
></font></p>
      <p align=3D"left"><font size=3D"+1">The volume of the tetrahedron is =
then </font></p>
      <blockquote>
        <p align=3D"left"><font size=3D"+1"><sup>1</sup>/<sub>3</sub>&nbsp;=
<img src=3D"https://mathcentral.uregina.ca/qq/database/qq.09.03/multiply.gi=
f" width=3D"10" height=3D"9">&nbsp;(the
          area of the base triangle)&nbsp;<img src=3D"https://mathcentral.u=
regina.ca/qq/database/qq.09.03/multiply.gif" width=3D"10" height=3D"9">&nbs=
p;0.75
          m<sup>3</sup></font></p>
      </blockquote>
      <p align=3D"left"><font size=3D"+1">The area of the base triangle can=
 be found using <a href=3D"https://mathcentral.uregina.ca/qq/database/QQ.09=
.01/bat1.html">Heron's
        Formula</a>.</font></p>
      <p align=3D"left"><font size=3D"+1">Penny</font></p>
      <!-- InstanceEndEditable --></td>
    <td width=3D"11%">&nbsp;</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>=20
    <td width=3D"13%">&nbsp;</td>
